{
  "texts": [
    "Scientific knowledge is primarily reported through academic journal articles, with scholars conventionally relying on journals to act as gatekeepers for academic research.",
    "Most journals not only filter for quality but also for topic, flagging this with their titles and aims.",
    "For example, the apparent scope of the Journal of Computational and Applied Mathematics can be guessed from its title, and this is narrowed down for the specialist in its Aims & Scope statements like, \"The main interest of the Journal is in papers that describe and analyse new computational techniques for solving scientific or engineering problems.",
    "[] The computational efficiency (e.g., the convergence, stability, accuracy, …) should be proved and illustrated by nontrivial numerical examples.\"",
    "foot_0 This information helps new authors seeking appropriate publication venues and readers seeking to browse relevant journals."
  ]
}